===Noun===
{{wikipedia|Mercury (element)}}
{{en-noun|~|mercuries}}

# A metal.
## A [[silvery]]-colored, toxic, [[metallic]] chemical element, [[liquid]] at room temperature, with atomic number 80 and symbol [[Hg]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
## {{label|en|science|historical}} One of the [[elemental]] principles formerly thought to be present in all [[metal]]s. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
## {{label|en|with definite article}} Ambient pressure or temperature (''from the use of mercury in [[barometer]]s and [[thermometer]]s''). {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
##: ''The '''mercury''' there has averaged 37.6C, 2.3C above the February norm.''
## {{label|en|obsolete}} [[liveliness|Liveliness]], [[volatility]]. {{defdate|17th-18th c.}}
##* Bishop Burnet
##*: He was so full of '''mercury''' that he could not fix long in any friendship, or to any design.
# A plant.
## An annual plant, {{taxlink|Mercurialis annua|species|noshow=1}}, formerly grown for its medicinal properties; [[French mercury]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##* '''1653''', {{w|Nicholas Culpeper}}, ''The English Physician Enlarged'', Folio Society 2007, p. 188:
##*: Towards the tops of the stalks and branches come forth at every joint in the male '''Mercury''' two small round green heads, standing together upon a short footstalk, which growing ripe are the seeds, not having any flower.
## A similar edible plant, {{taxlink|Chenopodium bonus-henricus|species|noshow=1}}, otherwise known as [[English mercury]] or [[allgood]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
## {{label|en|US|regional}} The [[poison oak]] or [[poison ivy]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}

